The Shared Facilities Manager and each Co-Tenant specifically agree that (i) either Co-Tenant may at any time pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, or grant a security interest in its own Undivided Interest and its rights under this Agreement to any Secured Party, and (ii) any Secured Party may exercise its rights under its agreement with a Co-Tenant who has pledged, collaterally assigned, encumbered or granted a security interest to such Secured Party in such Co-Tenant s Undivided Interest or rights under this Agreement, including foreclosing, receiving, transferring, conveying or assigning such Undivided Interest and rights hereunder, in each case without obtaining the consent of the other Co-Tenant or the Shared Facilities Manager but subject to obtaining any necessary third party consents and subject, in the case of clause (ii) above, to compliance with Section 7.2(ii) and (as to a Secured Party of either Co-Tenant other than ORNI 47), Section 7.2(iv). The Shared Facilities Manager and each Co-Tenant also agree that it shall, at any time and from time to time during the term of this Agreement, after receipt of a written request by either Co-Tenant, execute and deliver to the requesting Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant s Secured Party, as designated in such request, such estoppel certificates and consents as may be reasonably requested thereby. (b) Pledge, Collateral Assignment or Encumbrance. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, other than Section 13.24 of this Agreement, should a Co-Tenant pledge, collaterally assign, encumber or grant a security interest in its Undivided Interest and its rights under this Agreement as provided in Section 7.3(a) above, the Co-Tenants expressly agree between themselves and for the benefit of any Secured Party that (i) no Co-Tenant shall amend or attempt to amend this Agreement in any material respect unless the consent of all the Secured Parties is first obtained, (ii) upon the occurrence of a default by a Co-Tenant hereunder, the non-defaulting Co-Tenant declaring the default shall also provide written notice to the Secured Parties of such default (and accept the cure of such default by any Secured Party), (iii) each Secured Party shall have the same period after receipt of a notice of default to cure, or cause to be cured, the default described therein, as is given to the defaulting Co-Tenant, plus, in each instance, the following additional time periods: (a) thirty (30) days in the event of any monetary default; and (b) forty five (45) days in the event of any non-monetary default; provided, however, that such forty five (45) day period shall be extended for the time reasonably required by the Secured Party to complete such cure, so long as the Secured Party is diligently pursuing such cure, and (iv) in case of the termination of this Agreement as a result of any default or the bankruptcy, insolvency or appointment of a receiver in bankruptcy for a Co-Tenant (the "Insolvent Co-Tenant"), (1) the other Co-Tenant (the "Solvent Co-Tenant") shall give prompt notice of such termination to the Secured Party of the Insolvent Co-Tenant and (2) the Solvent Co-Tenants shall, upon written request of the first priority Secured Party of the Insolvent Co-Tenant with a lien on the Insolvent Secured Party's Project, made within sixty (60) days after such written notice to such Secured Party, enter into a new Shared Facilities and Shared Premises Agreement with such Secured Party, or its designee, within thirty (30) days after the receipt of such request. Such new Shared Facilities and Shared Premises Agreement shall be effective as of the date of the termination of this Agreement by reason of default by the Insolvent Co-Tenant, upon the same terms, covenants, conditions and agreements as contained in this Agreement. Upon the execution of any such new Shared Facilities and Shared Premises Agreement, the Secured Parties of the Insolvent Co-Tenant shall (A) pay the Solvent Co-Tenants any amounts which are due the Solvent Co-Tenants from the Insolvent Co-Tenant under the terms of this Agreement, (B) pay the Shared Facilities Manager any and all amounts which would have been due from the Insolvent Co-Tenant under this Agreement (had this Agreement not been terminated) to the date of the new Shared Facilities and Shared Premises Agreement, and (C) agree in writing to perform or cause to be performed all of the other covenants and agreements set forth in this Agreement to be performed by the Insolvent Co-Tenant to the extent that the Insolvent Co-Tenant failed to perform the same prior to the execution and delivery of the new Shared Facilities and Shared Premises Agreement. A Secured Party shall only be liable under this Agreement while it is in possession of or is the owner of an Undivided Interest, and only to the extent of its interest in the Insolvent Co-Tenant s assets. 7.4 Expenses. All reasonable expenses, including reasonable attorneys fees, incurred by the Shared Facilities Manager and the other Co-Tenant in connection with (a) the assignment or proposed assignment of a Co-Tenant s Undivided Interest and its rights under this Agreement, or (b) the actual or proposed pledge, collateral assignment, encumbrance, or grant of a security interest in a Co-Tenant s Undivided Interest and its rights under this Agreement to a Secured Party, shall be paid by the assigning/borrowing Co-Tenant to the other Co-Tenant, and the Shared Facilities Manager upon request therefor. ARTICLE 8 TERM AND TERMINATION 8.1 Term and Termination. The term of this Agreement shall commence as of the Effective Date and shall terminate upon the first occurrence of one of the following: (i) a single Co-Tenant becoming the owner of the entire ownership interest in all of the Co-Tenants' interest in the Undivided Transmission Line Grant, the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities, or (ii) the mutual agreement of all the Co-Tenants, with the written consent of the then existing Secured Parties. 8.2 Surrender and Assignment of Undivided Interest. (a) Either Co-Tenant may elect, but only with the consent of the Co-Tenant accepting the Undivided Interest, to convey its Undivided Interest and assign its rights hereunder and under the Undivided Transmission Line Grant to such other Co-Tenant and, thereupon, to cease to have any right, title or interest in the Undivided Transmission Line Grant, the Shared Premises, the Shared Facilities or its Undivided Interest; provided that such conveyance is made by one Co-Tenant hereto, as the Surrendering Co-Tenant, to the other Co-Tenant hereto, and further provided that (A) the Surrendering Co-Tenant executes and delivers all instruments of transfer as may be necessary or appropriate to effect (and that do effect) the conveyance of its Undivided Interest and assignment of its rights hereunder and under the Undivided Transmission Line Grant to, and which are reasonably satisfactory to, the remaining Co-Tenant, (B) such assignment and conveyance is accompanied by an assignment by the Surrendering Co-Tenant to the assignee Co-Tenant of all its rights under this Agreement and under the Undivided Transmission Line Grant, (C) an encumbered Undivided Interest may only be surrendered with the written consent of each Secured Party that holds a security interest in such Undivided Interest and a release of such Secured Party s security interest being provided by such Secured Party, (D) such assignment does not violate the terms of the Undivided Transmission Line Grant, and (E) such assignment is permitted by the Don A. Campbell 1 PPA and the Proposed Don A. Campbell 2 PPA. The Surrendering Co-Tenant shall remain fully responsible for, and shall pay its Proportionate Share of, all Shared O&M Expenses through the effective date of its surrender of its Undivided Interest. No surrender of a Co-Tenant s Undivided Interest shall relieve the surrendering Co-Tenant of any of its obligations under any agreement, unless expressly provided for in this Agreement, or in a writing between the Co-Tenants. (b) The Co-Tenants agree that subject to compliance with Sections 7.2(ii), (iv), (v), and (vi) and, solely in the event ORNI 37 has any Secured Party, Section 7.2(vii), ORNI 37 shall be entitled to convey its entire Undivided Interest to any of its Affiliates which entitles such Affiliate to use the Shared Facilities for development of the Don A. Campbell 2 Project. Such entire Undivided Interest shall be freely assignable to an Affiliate of Ormat Nevada Inc., a Delaware corporation, subject to compliance with Sections 7.2(ii), (iv), (v), and (vi) and, solely in the event ORNI 37 has any Secured Party, Section 7.2(vii), or to the other Co-Tenant hereto in accordance with Section 8.2(a)). Upon receipt of its Undivided Interest, such Affiliate shall execute a joinder agreement in the form of Exhibit C attached hereto, pursuant to which such Affiliate agrees to become a Co-Tenant and be bound by this Agreement and ORNI 37. 8.3 Abandonment or Decommissioning of a Project. In addition to the obligations of the Surrendering Co-Tenant set forth in Section 8.2 (unless the assignee Co-Tenant expressly assumes such obligations) and in the event a Co-Tenant desires to decommission and abandon its Project, and the Undivided Interest of such Co-Tenant is not accepted by the other Co-Tenant, the Surrendering Co-Tenant shall, upon notice to the other Co-Tenant of its intent to abandon its Project be responsible for (i) the release of its interest in the Undivided Transmission Line Grant if such interest is not being assumed by the receiving Co-Tenant, and upon the failure of the Surrendering Co-Tenant to release same, the Shared Facilities Manager may release same on behalf of such Surrendering Co-Tenant and shall charge the Surrendering Co-Tenant all costs incurred to accomplish such release, plus ten percent (10%) of such costs, and (ii) its Proportionate Share (as of the date notice of intent to abandon and decommission its Project is given to the other Co-Tenant) of the Shared O&M Expenses, including any anticipated cost of decommissioning and removing the Shared Facilities and restoration of the Shared Premises (collectively, the "Withdrawal Costs"). The Shared Facilities Manager shall administer the calculation, collection, and distribution of the Withdrawal Costs, as follows: (a) The Shared Facilities Manager shall calculate the Withdrawal Costs and shall provide written notice of same to the Surrendering Co-Tenant within forty five (45) days after the Shared Facilities Manager has received notice of the Surrendering Co-Tenant s intent to abandon its Project. (b) The Surrendering Co-Tenant shall, within thirty (30) days of the receipt of the written notice of the Withdrawal Costs, pay the Withdrawal Costs to the Shared Facilities Manager. The Withdrawal Costs payment shall be held in trust and be maintained by the Shared Facilities Manager in a reserve account and used by the Shared Facilities Manager for the payment of Shared O&M Expenses (to the extent such amounts were collected from the Surrendering Co-Tenant as provided above), including decommissioning and removal of the Shared Facilities and the restoration of the Shared Premises when same becomes necessary. (c) Any dispute in regard to the amount of the Withdrawal Costs shall be submitted to dispute resolution pursuant to the terms of Article 12. (d) Any failure to pay the Withdrawal Costs shall constitute a default hereunder and a Co-Tenant shall forfeit all of its Undivided Interests hereunder to the other Co-Tenant and shall immediately cease and desist from the use of the Shared Facilities. The Surrendering Co-Tenant further irrevocably appoints the Shared Facilities Manager as its true and lawful attorney, with full power of substitution, for the sole use and benefit of the remaining Co-Tenant, but at the Surrendering Co-Tenant s expense, to the extent permitted by law to exercise, at any time and from time to time while Surrendering Co-Tenant s default has occurred and is continuing, the power to sell, transfer, assign or otherwise deal in or with the Undivided Interests of the Surrendering Co-Tenant or the proceeds thereof, as fully and effectually as if the Shared Facilities Manager were the absolute owner thereof, provided that the Shared Facilities Manager shall give to the Surrendering Co-Tenant not less than ten (10) days' prior written notice of the time and place of a sale or other intended transfer or disposition of any of the Undivided Interest of the Surrendering Co-Tenant. Any Undivided Interest of the Surrendering Co-Tenant transferred to the other Co-Tenant under this Section 8.3(d) shall be allocated to the remaining Co-Tenants on a pro rata basis in accordance with their relative Undivided Interests prior to such allocation. 8.4 Distribution on Termination of this Agreement. In the event that the Co-Tenants decide to decommission all of the Projects and to proceed with the removal of the Shared Facilities, the Shared Facilities Manager shall take account of all of the Co-Tenants joint assets, including the Shared Premises, the Shared Facilities, and joint liabilities and shall proceed with the liquidation thereof. The assets shall be liquidated under the supervision of the Shared Facilities Manager as promptly as is consistent with obtaining a reasonable value therefor, and the proceeds therefrom, together with any assets distributed in-kind, shall be applied and distributed as follows: (a) To the payment of debts and liabilities of the Co-Tenants in connection with the Shared Facilities which are then due and the expenses of liquidation. (b) To the setting up of any reserves which the Shared Facilities Manager deems reasonably necessary for any contingent or unforeseen liabilities or obligations or debts not yet payable by the Co-Tenants in connection with the Shared Facilities, including any reserves to pay costs associated with the decommissioning and removal of the Shared Facilities. (c) Any sum remaining shall be distributed to the Co-Tenants, pro rata based upon each Co-Tenant s Proportionate Share as of the date of final termination of this Agreement. (d) The Shared Facilities Manager shall have the right, in order to effectuate the liquidation of the assets, to disconnect the Shared Facilities from the Interconnection Facilities and the Projects. 8.5 Valuation and Distribution of Non-Cash Distributions. To the extent that non-cash consideration is distributed in kind pursuant to this Agreement, the fair value of such assets shall first be determined by an independent valuation expert selected by the Co-Tenants, and the distribution of assets shall be made in accordance with such valuation. If the Co-Tenants cannot agree on the selection of an independent valuation expert, such dispute shall be resolved pursuant to Article 12 hereof. ARTICLE 9 DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 9.1 Co-Tenant Default. A Co-Tenant shall be in default under this Agreement if such Co-Tenant: (a) Fails to pay when due any amounts required to be paid by such Co-Tenant under the terms of this Agreement and such failure to pay is not cured within fifteen (15) days following written notice from the Shared Facilities Manager or any other Co-Tenant specifying the amount to be paid, provided that such period shall be extended for so long as the allegedly defaulting Co-Tenant is disputing in good faith such amount pursuant to the procedures set forth in Article 12 hereof; (b) Breaches, or causes the breach of the Undivided Transmission Line Grant and fails to cure such breach within the time permitted by the Undivided Transmission Line Grant, provided that promptly after receiving written notice of any breach the defaulting Co-Tenant shall provide a copy thereof to the Shared Facilities Manager and the other Co-Tenant; (c) Fails to cure any other failure to perform under this Agreement within thirty (30) days following written notice from the Shared Facilities Manager or any other Co-Tenant specifying the nature of the failure to perform, provided that if the default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days, then the default shall be deemed cured if such default is capable of cure and the defaulting Co-Tenant commences, diligently pursues, and completes action that remedies the default within ninety (90) days of receipt of such notice; (d) Makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files a petition in bankruptcy, voluntarily takes advantage of any bankruptcy or insolvency laws or is adjudicated bankrupt or judicially insolvent, in each case, immediately upon such occurrence or, if a petition or an answer is filed proposing the adjudication of such Co-Tenant as bankrupt, when such Co-Tenant shall consent to the filing thereof or fail to discharge such petition or filing within sixty (60) days after the filing thereof; (e) Any substantial part of such Co-Tenant s property is subjected to any levy, seizure, assignment or sale for or by any creditor or Governmental Authority that materially affects that Co-Tenant s ability to perform under this Agreement; or Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, the foregoing notice of default shall not be effective, and the period of time within which the defaulting Co-Tenant may cure the noticed default shall not commence to run, unless and until a copy of said notice of default is provided to any Secured Party who holds a deed of trust encumbering or a security interest in the defaulting Co-Tenant s Undivided Interest who has provided written notice of its notice address to the other Co-Tenant and the Shared Facilities Manager. The non defaulting Co-Tenant and the Shared Facilities Manager shall accept curative performance from any such Secured Party within the time periods provided for in Section 7.3 or in any consent to assignment executed by the Co-Tenants and the Shared Facilities Manager. 9.2 Shared Facilities Manager Defaults. The Shared Facilities Manager shall be in default under this Agreement if the Shared Facilities Manager: (a) Fails to pay when due any amounts required to be paid by the Shared Facilities Manager under the terms of this Agreement and such failure to pay is not cured within fifteen (15) days following written notice from either Co-Tenant specifying the amount to be paid, provided that such period shall be extended for so long as the Shared Facilities Manager is disputing in good faith such amount pursuant to the procedures set forth in Article 12 hereof; (b) Breaches, or causes the breach of a Transmission Line Agreement and fails to cure such breach within the time permitted by such Transmission Line Agreement, provided that promptly after receiving written notice of any breach the Shared Facilities Manager shall provide a copy thereof to the Co-Tenants; (c) Fails to cure any other failure to perform under this Agreement within thirty (30) days following written notice from a Co-Tenant specifying the nature of the failure to perform, provided that if the default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days but is capable of cure, then the default shall be deemed cured if the Shared Facilities Manager commences, diligently pursues, and completes action that remedies the default within ninety (90) days of receipt of such notice; (d) Makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files a petition in bankruptcy, voluntarily takes advantage of any bankruptcy or insolvency laws or is adjudicated bankrupt or judicially insolvent, in each case, immediately upon such occurrence or, if a petition or an answer is filed proposing the adjudication of such the Shared Facilities Manager as bankrupt, when the Shared Facilities Manager shall consent to the filing thereof or fail to discharge such petition or answer within sixty (60) days after the filing thereof unless the same shall have been discharged or denied prior thereto; (e) Has any substantial part of its property subjected to any levy, seizure, assignment or sale for or by any creditor or Governmental Authority that materially affects the Shared Facilities Manager s ability to perform under this Agreement; (a) In the event of a default by a Co-Tenant, the non defaulting Co-Tenant and the Shared Facilities Manager on behalf of itself or the other Co-Tenant each shall have the following remedies, exercisable only after due inquiry that a default has occurred and is continuing: (1) In its sole and absolute discretion, to cure the default of the defaulting Co-Tenant by making or tendering the required payment or performance, and permitting the defaulting Co-Tenant s Project to remain connected to the Shared Facilities and sales of electricity by the defaulting Co-Tenant s Project to be continued, provided that any such amounts paid by the non-defaulting Co-Tenant(s) shall be treated as a loan to the defaulting Co-Tenant, which loan shall be payable on demand and accrue interest until repaid in full at the Default Interest Rate; (2) To demand disconnection of the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project from the Shared Facilities in accordance with Section 4.5 hereof, provided that the defaulting Co-Tenant shall be permitted to reconnect its Project once the default is cured and any and all damage suffered and incurred by the non-defaulting Co-Tenant and the Shared Facilities Manager have been compensated, together with interest at the Default Interest Rate until paid in full; (3) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; or (4) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which the non-defaulting Co-Tenant or the Shared Facilities Manager might otherwise have at law or in equity. (b) In the event of default by the Shared Facilities Manager, each Co-Tenant shall have the following remedies, exercisable only after due inquiry that a default has occurred and is continuing: (1) To remove the Shared Facilities Manager for cause, as permitted by Section 5.3; (2) In its sole discretion, to cure the default of the Shared Facilities Manager, provided any amounts paid, together with interest at the Default Interest Rate until paid in full, shall be recoverable from the Shared Facilities Manager; (3) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; or (4) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which any one or more of the Co-Tenants might otherwise have at law or in equity. (c) All of the foregoing remedies are cumulative and non-exclusive, and the exercise of any one remedy at any one time shall not constitute the waiver of any other remedy at a later or different time. 9.4 Partition. The Co-Tenants each acknowledge and agree that it would be prejudicial to the interests of the Co-Tenants under this Agreement if either Co-Tenant were to seek partition or any other type of division of the Undivided Transmission Line Grant, the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities, or file an action for such partition or division. ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Use of FA&R LGIA. The FA&R LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of electricity generated by or on behalf of a Project owned by a Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant's successors or assigns) at the Excelsior 120 kV Substation. Each Co-Tenant shall have an undivided ownership interest as tenant-in-common in the rights and obligations of the Interconnection Customer and the FA&R LGIA equal to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, and possess an undivided right to enjoy all of such interest in the Interconnection Customer under the FA&R LGIA. 2.2 Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Project to the Excelsior 120 kV Substation to the extent such interconnection will result in such Co-Tenant having a Project with a Net Nameplate Capacity in excess of the product of (i) such Co-Tenant's Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest and (ii) the Interconnection Capacity. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant generating energy from its respective Project in excess of its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity, then such Co-Tenant shall curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity. 2.3 Curtailment. In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of NV Energy, such curtailment shall be allocated first to ORNI 37 according to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity; ORNI 47 shall not be curtailed unless and until the curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of NV Energy exceeds ORNI 37's Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity; provided however, if (a) the need for the interruption or reduction can in accordance with Good Utility Practice be attributed to a particular Co-Tenant's Project or portions of its Project, then the Manager shall allocate such interruption or reduction to such Project, or (b) a different allocation is necessary to comply with the FA&R LGIA or the Transmission Utility direction pursuant to the FA&R LGIA, then the Manager shall allocate such interruption or reduction in accordance with the FA&R LGIA or the Transmission Utility's direction, as applicable. Each Co-Tenant shall promptly effect such interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 2.3 upon notice from the Manager, which notice shall be reasonable under the circumstances. In the event notice is impracticable or a Co-Tenant fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager may effect the same by direct action. 2.4 FA&R LGIA Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the periodic payment of all expenses incurred under the FA&R LGIA in accordance with its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. (a) Construction Costs. ORNI 37 hereby agrees to fund all Construction Costs, and agrees to design, engineer and construct the Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities required to be designed, engineered, and constructed as a result of the FA&R LGIA. (b) FA&R LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its pro rata share of the FA&R LGIA Operating Expenses according to such Co-Tenant's Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. (c) Payment of FA&R LGIA Operating Expenses. The Manager shall, as authorized agent for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection and payment of the FA&R LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts due from the Interconnection Customer under the FA&R LGIA. Each Co-Tenant obligated to pay FA&R LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts under the FA&R LGIA shall pay for FA&R LGIA costs promptly upon receipt of a written payment notice from the Manager, but in any event within thirty (30) days of such receipt or such earlier time as required by the FA&R LGIA. 2.5 Liquidated Damages; Credits; Refunds. To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the FA&R LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant's Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant). 2.6 Several Liability. Each Co-Tenant shall be severally liable for (i) any payments due under the FA&R LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the FA&R LGIA and each Party shall be severally liable for all other obligations hereunder. 2.7 Indemnity. (a) Each Co-Tenant (an "Indemnifying Co-Tenant") shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenant (each, an "Indemnified Co-Tenant") from and against any and all losses (including all lost revenues under applicable PPAs), damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees (collectively, "Claims"), which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant in connection with any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement, its applicable PPA or the FA&R LGIA. (b) The Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager. 2.8 Taxes. Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Project, except for any taxes or assessments that are FA&R LGIA Operating Expenses. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided if a Co-Tenant in good faith contests or disputes such taxes or assessments and furnishes to the other Co-Tenant a bond or other acceptable security in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested taxes or assessments, such Co-Tenant will not be in default under this Section 2.8 for failing to timely pay such contested taxes or assessments. 2.9 Operation and Management. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Project Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (a) in accordance with the terms of the FA&R LGIA and its applicable PPA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, (c) in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended ("FPA"), and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the NV Energy Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the FA&R LGIA. (b) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the FA&R LGIA, including with respect to its obligations to fund FA&R LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall obtain and maintain status as an "exempt wholesale generator" or a "qualifying facility" under applicable Law. (c) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to Manager as agent for the Co-Tenants under the FA&R LGIA, and shall provide Manager such information required by Manager to comply with its obligations under the FA&R LGIA. (d) With respect to jointly held assets, the Co-Tenants may delegate to the Manager some or all of their respective obligations under this Agreement. 2.10 Events of Default; Default. The following shall constitute "Events of Default": a Party fails to perform its obligations under this Agreement or the FA&R LGIA in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such default within (i) ten (10) days after receipt of written notice of a payment default, or (ii) twenty (20) days after receipt of written notice of any non-payment default, provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations other than a payment default is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then such Co-Tenant shall not be in default under this Section 2.10 if it commences to cure such default within twenty (20) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed sixty (60) days, including the initial cure period. 2.11 Remedies. Subject to the last sentence of Section 5.8, in addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative), following an Event of Default, each non-defaulting Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, to perform the obligations of the defaulting Party, and the defaulting Party shall reimburse the performing Parties for their expenses which they incurred in rendering the performance, plus interest at the Interest Rate. 2.12 Disconnection. (a) If a Co-Tenant fails to cure any default of it under this Agreement or the FA&R LGIA within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of such default, the Manager may disconnect the breaching Co-Tenant's Project from the Interconnection Facilities leading to the Excelsior 120 kV Substation (i) after obtaining written approval to do so from the Co-Tenant then not in default, or (ii) without approval from the Co-Tenant then not in default but only to the extent necessary to prevent or cure a "Default" under the FA&R LGIA; provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then the Manager may not disconnect the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project if such Co-Tenant commences to cure such default within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed eighty five (85) days, including the initial cure period; provided further, that in no event shall any cure period hereunder extend beyond any applicable cure period under the FA&R LGIA. (b) To the extent caused by a Co-Tenant's default hereunder, the Manager may also disconnect such Co-Tenant's Project in order to prevent damage to the other Co-Tenant's Project, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of NV Energy or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Projects; the Manager shall immediately notify the Co-Tenants of any such disconnection. (c) The Manager shall have the power and authority to disconnect a Project (i) if the Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that disconnection is necessary in the event of an Emergency, or (ii) at the direction of NV Energy pursuant to rights under the FA&R LGIA. In the cases of (1) a real or reasonably perceived Emergency as described in clause (i) above or (2) as directed under clause (ii) above, the Manager shall provide notice to the relevant Co-Tenant concurrently with disconnection of its Project or immediately following the disconnection of its Project. 2.13 Equitable Relief. The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for a breach by the Manager or any other Party of its respective obligations under this Agreement, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Party or the Manager to prevent or eliminate such default. 2.14 Dispute Resolution. (a) Submission. In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement or the FA&R LGIA, such Party (the "Disputing Party") shall provide the other Parties with written notice of the dispute or claim ("Notice of Dispute"). Such dispute or claim shall be referred to a designated senior representative of each Party for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable after receipt of the Notice of Dispute by the Parties. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the claim or dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) days of the other Parties' receipt of the Notice of Dispute, such claim or dispute may, upon mutual agreement of the Parties, be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. In the event the Parties do not agree within such thirty (30) day period to submit such claim or dispute to arbitration, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. (b) Arbitration Procedures. Any arbitration initiated under this Agreement shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties. The arbitrator shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including electric transmission, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator shall provide each of the Parties an opportunity to be heard and, except as otherwise provided herein, shall conduct the arbitration in accordance with the rules and procedures for arbitration of complex business disputes for Judicial Arbitration and Mediation Services, Inc. ("Arbitration Rules") and any applicable FERC regulations; provided, however, in the event of a conflict between the Arbitration Rules and the terms of this Section 2.14, the terms of this Section 2.14 shall prevail. (c) Arbitration Decisions. Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties, the arbitrator shall render a decision within ninety (90) days of appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefor. The arbitrator shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and the FA&R LGIA and shall have no power to modify or change any provision of such agreements in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The decision of the arbitrator may be appealed solely on the grounds that the conduct of the arbitrator, or the decision itself, violated the standards set forth in the Federal Arbitration Act or the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act. The final decision of the arbitrator must also be filed with FERC if it affects jurisdictional rates, terms and conditions of service, Interconnection Facilities, or Network Upgrades. (d) Costs. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and for such Co-Tenant's Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the cost of the arbitrator chosen, if applicable. 2.15 Effect of Force Majeure. If, because of an event of Force Majeure, any Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this Agreement, and if such Party promptly gives the other Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in detail, specifying the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the non-payment obligations and liabilities of the Party giving such notice and the corresponding obligations and liabilities of any other Party shall be temporarily suspended to the extent made necessary by and during the continuance of such Force Majeure; provided, that in no event will the suspension of a Party's obligations and liabilities hereunder be permitted to cause a "Default" under the FA&R LGIA. Any disabling effects of such event of Force Majeure shall be eliminated as soon as and to the extent reasonably practicable by the Party claiming Force Majeure. 2.16 Notice of Default. Each Co-Tenant and the Manager shall promptly provide written notice to the other Parties upon receiving notice of, or otherwise discovering, any default or potential default under this Agreement or the FA&R LGIA or receiving any other notice under the FA&R LGIA. The Manager shall specifically be indemnified by the Co-Tenants (pro rata in accordance with their Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests) and held harmless from any and all actions taken by the Manager in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of the Manager's attorneys or accountants, and shall be reimbursed by the Co-Tenants (pro rata in accordance with their Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests) for costs, which arise in connection with the FA&R LGIA or this Agreement (other than costs resulting from a material breach by the Manager of this Agreement or the fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager). 3.4 Books and Records; Reporting Requirements. The Manager shall, from time to time or at the reasonable request of the Co-Tenants or their Financing Parties, provide reports to the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties sufficient to keep the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the FA&R LGIA, the Construction Costs and the FA&R LGIA Operating Costs. 3.5 Replacement of Manager. Upon the written approval of both Co-Tenants, the Co-Tenants may replace the Manager with any Person of their choosing; provided, however, that any Co-Tenant (acting by itself) may remove the Manager if the Manager is in material default hereunder. Upon any replacement of the then-existing Manager, the then existing-Manager shall no longer be a Party hereunder and the new-Manager appointed by the Co-Tenants shall be the Manager hereunder. The Manager shall perform its obligations under this Agreement (a) in accordance with the terms of the FA&R LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, (c) in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the FPA, and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the NV Energy Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the FA&R LGIA. 3.9 Termination of FA&R LGIA. ORNI 37 LLC RATE SCHEDULE FERC NO. 1 1. Availability. ORNI 37 LLC ("Seller") will make electric energy and capacity available under this Rate Schedule to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. 2. Applicability. This Rate Schedule is applicable to all sales of energy and capacity by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of Seller. 3. Rates. All sales shall be made at the rates established between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Ancillary Services. Seller may offer for sale those ancillary services in those markets specified and authorized by the Commission from time to time in orders extending such authority to all sellers authorized to sell electric energy and capacity at market-based rates, including: a. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. b. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. c. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. d. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. e. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. ("SPP") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g. Ancillary Services - Third Party Provider Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Primary Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 6. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; Part 41; Part 101, with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects; and Part 141, except sections 141.14 and 141.15; and received blanket approval under Part 34. ORNI 37 LLC, ER15-2330-000 (2015). 8. Effective Date. This Rate Schedule is effective on the date specified by the Commission. 9. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northwest region and a Category 1 seller in all other regions, as defined in 18 CFR 35.36(a).
